data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

**Sync I/O on the Cosmos DB provider is fully removed.** In .NET 10 you could opt in to sync-over-async; in EF Core 11 that opt-in is gone. Every synchronous call **always throws** — no workaround.

Your four methods all break:

| Method | Broken Call | Fix |
|--------|------------|-----|
| `GetAll()` | `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `GetById()` | `First(...)` | `await FirstAsync(...)` |
| `GetCount()` | `Count()` | `await CountAsync()` |
| `Save()` | `Add` + `SaveChanges()` | `Add` + `await SaveChangesAsync()` |

Here's the migrated repository:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- All return types become `Task<T>` (or `Task` for void)
- Method names should follow the `Async` suffix convention
- **All callers** up the chain must also be updated to `await` these methods — this change propagates through your entire call stack
